'''Frances F. Berdan''' (born May 31, 1944) is an American [[archaeologist]] specializing in the [[Aztec]]s and professor emerita of anthropology at [[California State University, San Bernardino]].<ref>http://phonebook.csusb.edu/FacultyProfile.aspx?ID=245</ref>

Berdan has authored many influential books about the Aztec civilization. In 1983, she received an "Outstanding Professor" award from California State University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://csulaahsmesoamericanconference2012.wordpress.com/tag/frances-berdan/|title=Frances Berdan - CSULA AHS Mesoamerican Conference 2012|website=csulaahsmesoamericanconference2012.wordpress.com}}</ref> In 1986, she was a fellow at [[Dumbarton Oaks]] with [[Michael E. Smith]] and other prominent Mesoamerican scholars. The result of that stay was the book ''Aztec Imperial Strategies'' (1986).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doaks.org/research/library-archives/dumbarton-oaks-archives/historical-records/oral-history-project/frances-berdan|title=Frances Berdan — Dumbarton Oaks|first=James N.|last=Carder|website=www.doaks.org}}</ref>

