{{Infobox writer |name = Marie-Claire Daveluy |image = Marie-Claire Daveluy.jpg |birth_date = {{birth date|1880|08|15}} |birth_place = Montreal, Quebec, Canada |death_date = {{date of death and age|1968|01|21|1880|08|15}} |death_place = Montreal, Quebec, Canada |nationality = Canada |occupation = librarian |genre = youth historical novel}}
'''Marie-Claire Daveluy''' (August 15, 1880 &ndash; January 21, 1968) was a Canadian librarian, historian and writer.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=FeflDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1847 |title=Creative Canada: A Biographical Dictionary of Twentieth-century Creative and Performing Artists |pages=1847–49 |volume=Volume 1 |year=1971 |ISBN=1442637838}}</ref> She is considered a pioneer in [[library science]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.academiedeslettresduquebec.ca/membres/marie-claire-daveluy-74 |title=Marie-Claire Daveluy |publisher=Académie des lettres du Québec |language=fr}}</ref>
The daughter of Georges Daveluy and Marie Lesieur Desaulniers, she was born in [[Montreal]] and was educated at the Hochelaga Convent. She earned a degree in library science at [[McGill University]] in 1920. At the [[Montreal Public Libraries Network|Bibliothèque municipale de Montréal]], she was assistant librarian from 1920 to 1943 and head of cataloguing from 1930 to 1941. In 1937, with [[Aegidius Fauteux]], she founded the École de bibliothécaires at the [[Université de Montréal]] and served as its chair for several years. She also helped found the Association canadienne des bibliothécaires de langue française in 1943. She hosted a weekly program of historical sketches on [[Ici Radio-Canada Première|Radio-Canada]] from 1943 to 1948. Daveluy contributed articles to various periodicals including the ''{{ill|Revue d'histoire de l'Amérique française|fr}}'', ''La Bonne Parole'', ''L'Oiseau bleu'' and ''[[L'Action nationale|L'action française]]''. Her novels for youth combined Canadian history with romantic fiction. She also published a number of fairy tales including ''Le Filleul du roi Grolo'', ''Sur les ailes de l'oiseau bleu'' and ''Une Révolte au pays des fées''.<ref name=archives/><ref name=montreal>{{cite web |url=https://archivesdemontreal.ica-atom.org/daveluy-marie-claire-1880-1968 |title=Daveluy, Marie-Claire |work=Catalogue des archives de la Ville de Montréal |language=fr}}</ref>
She was the first woman to become a member of the Montreal Historical Society. In 1924, she received the {{ill|Prix David|fr}} for her historical novel ''Aventures de Perrine et Charlot''. In 1934, she received the Prix de l'[[Académie Française]] and a second Prix David for ''Jeanne-Mance, 1606-1673''.<ref name=archives>{{cite web |url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/literaryarchives/027011-200.034-e.html |title=Marie-Claire Daveluy fonds |publisher=Library and Archives Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/women/030001-1352-e.html |title=Marie-Claire Daveluy |work=Celebrating Women's Achievements |publisher=Library and Archives Canada}}</ref><ref name=montreal/>
She died in Montreal at the age of 87.
