'''Thomas Leland''' (1722–1785) was an [[Ireland|Irish]] historian, translator and academic and the author of the early [[Gothic fiction|gothic novel]] ''Longsword, Earl of Salisbury: An Historical Romance'', published in 1762.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=WAY1AAAAMAAJ&dq=thomas+leland&printsec=frontcover&source=web&ots=He4uOG4DuQ&sig=xy_ctMzXY06utrqPXYNPGb9dqZQ#PPA36,M1 Leland]</ref><ref>"...some would argue that Thomas Leland's ''Longsword, Earl of Salisbury'' (1762) -subtitled "A Historical Romance"-is really the first Gothic novel". Rictor Norton, ''Gothic Readings : the first wave, 1764-1840''. London. Leicester University Press, 2000. {{ISBN|0718502167}}  (p.1)</ref>

He was born in [[Dublin]] and educated at [[Thomas Sheridan (divine)|Thomas Sheridan's]] school<ref name="rico">[http://www.ricorso.net/rx/az-data/authors/l/Leland_T/life.htm  A life - Thomas Leland(1722-1785)]</ref> and then at [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]], where he became Professor of Oratory in 1763. He translated the Orations of [[Demosthenes]] in three volumes and wrote a life of [[Philip of Macedon]] in 1758.  He wrote an influential ''History of Ireland from the Invasion of [[Henry II of England|Henry II]]'' in 1773.  His portrait, by John Dean, is held by the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>The Concise Oxford Companion to Irish Literature. Oxford University Press.</ref>

Leland was made a fellow of Trinity College Dublin in 1746.<ref name="rico" />
He was ordained a [[Church of Ireland]] priest in 1748, he served as vicar in Bray, Co. Wicklow, in 1773 he was appointed Vicar of [[St. Ann's Church, Dawson Street]], in Dublin.<ref>''Church of Ireland Notes'', Irish Times, 4 August 2012.
</ref>

